<!-- FAQ Page for Authenticated Users -->
<main class="existing-page">
  <div class="page-header">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-authenticated-container">
  <!-- Getting Started -->
  <div class="faq-auth-category">
    <h3 class="faq-auth-category-title">Getting Started</h3>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="1">What is this tool?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">This is a platform for creating, publishing, and collecting survey responses enhanced by interactive visualizations. It allows creators to design custom survey questions, from multiple choice to clickable sections on images, and then share them through a unique link.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="2">What is a visualization?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A visualization is an image that the survey taker can interact with in some way. This might be selectable regions of the image, or it might be as simple as panning or zooming in and out of the image.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Survey Design -->
  <div class="faq-auth-category">
    <h3 class="faq-auth-category-title">Survey Design</h3>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="3">What is a survey design?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A survey design is a series of questions put together that acts as a template from which surveys can be published from. The survey design is not publicly available and can only be interacted with by the survey designer.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="8">How is the title different from the name?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">The title of the survey is what the participant sees when they take it. The name of the survey is only seen on the designer account.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="13">What does it mean to import a visualization?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A visualization from your account may be selected and attached to the given question. Changes to the visualization in the question edit page will be specific to that question.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Questions -->
  <div class="faq-auth-category">
    <h3 class="faq-auth-category-title">Questions</h3>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="9">How is a question displayed?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">On the left side of the page will be the attached visualization (if there is one). On the right side will be the question, the response prompt/field, and a comment box (if included).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="10">What is the question type?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">The question type is the format in which a participant responds to the question.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="11">What is a survey comment?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A survey comment is an optional response section for a user to add any comments they may have about a specific survey question.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="12">What does it mean for a question to be required?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A participant must leave a response in order to continue, and the response must match the min/max parameters (if they exist). To disable a min/max, set it to 0.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Publishing & Sharing -->
  <div class="faq-auth-category">
    <h3 class="faq-auth-category-title">Publishing & Sharing</h3>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="4">What is a published survey?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A published survey is a survey design that has been pushed out and can now be taken by users it is shared with. It is not editable. To release a changed version, the original design must be changed and a new survey must be published.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="5">How do I publish a survey?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A survey must be published through a survey design. To publish a survey design, scroll to the bottom of its overview page and click 'publish.'</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="6">How can I share a survey?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">Once you publish a survey, you will be provided with a link to the survey. You can send this out to participants via email or any other communication medium to have users take your survey.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="14">What happens when I publish a survey?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">The survey will be made available for completion in the specified time frame. The published survey will follow the state of the design at the time of publication, and it is accessible through a shareable link.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Survey Status & Format -->
  <div class="faq-auth-category">
    <h3 class="faq-auth-category-title">Survey Status & Format</h3>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="7">What is the format of a survey?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A survey starts with a page presenting its title and introduction text. Then, it has a page for each question which a participant must navigate through one-by-one. After the last question, the conclusion text is presented.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="15">What are the opening and closing times of a survey?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A survey may only be completed between its opening time and its closing time.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-auth-item">
      <h4 class="faq-auth-question" id="16">What does the status of a survey mean?</h4>
      <p class="faq-auth-answer">A survey's status can be "pending," "in-progress," or "closed." "Pending" means the opening date/time is still in the future and the survey has not opened for completion yet. "In-progress" means it is currently open. "Closed" means the closing date/time has passed and the survey is no longer open for completion.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  </div>
</main>
